'''Federal law''' is the body of [[law]] created by the [[federal government]] of a country. A federal government is formed when a group of political units, such as [[state (subnational)|states]] or [[provinces]] join together in a [[federation]], delegating their individual [[sovereignty]] and many powers to the [[central government]] while retaining or reserving other limited powers. As a result, two or more levels of government exist within an established geographic territory. The body of law of the common central government is the federal law.

Examples of federal governments include those of [[Australia]], [[Brazil]], [[Canada]], [[Germany]], [[Malaysia]], [[Pakistan]], [[Republic of India]], [[Russia]], the former [[Soviet Union]] and the [[United States]].

== United States ==
{{Main|Law of the United States}}

The [[United States Constitution]] provides for a [[federal government]] that is superior to [[state government]]s with regard to its [[enumerated powers]]. These powers include the authority to govern [[international relations|international affairs]], [[commerce clause|interstate commerce]], the [[currency]] and [[defense (military)|national defense]]. After the [[American Civil War]], the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] applied the Constitution's [[United States Bill of Rights|Bill of Rights]] to state governments. Legislation passed by [[United States Congress|Congress]], an [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Order]] of the [[President of the United States|President]], or a decision of [[United States federal courts|federal courts]] pursuant to the Constitution are federal law.

Through the system of checks and balances, it is the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] makes final decisions regarding [[Law of the United States|federal laws]] regarding specific cases brought before them.  United States federal laws are [[Codification (law)|codified]] in the [[United States Code]].

